## Module 5: Anomaly Detection with Machine Learning

### Learning Objectives
- ✓ Explain why static thresholds fail in dynamic environments
- ✓ Train an Isolation Forest model on multi-dimensional telemetry
- ✓ Visualize anomalies in compute and network data
- ✓ Compare Isolation Forest with Z-score and moving average approaches

### Core Topics
- Static thresholds vs dynamic anomaly detection
- Unsupervised learning for operations: no labeled data needed
- Isolation Forest: how it isolates outliers by random splits
- Z-score: standard deviation-based anomaly detection
- Moving average: smoothing noise, detecting trends
- Multi-dimensional telemetry: CPU + memory + network + disk together
- Contamination parameter: tuning false positive rate

### Isolation Forest Lab
Load a CSV with CPU, memory, network, and disk metrics. Train scikit-learn `IsolationForest` with contamination=0.05. Predict anomalies. Plot results with Matplotlib — normal points in blue, anomalies in red.

### Z-Score & Moving Average Lab
Implement Z-score anomaly detection: flag any data point > 3 standard deviations. Implement moving average with a 10-point window: flag points outside the rolling band. Compare results with Isolation Forest.

### Break / Fix Activity
Inject synthetic anomalies into the dataset (CPU spike to 99%, memory leak pattern, disk fill). Run all 3 detection methods. Compare: which method catches each anomaly type best?

