## Module 9: Predictive Maintenance & Capacity Planning

### Learning Objectives
- ✓ Forecast CPU, memory, and disk usage using time-series models
- ✓ Calculate when infrastructure will hit capacity limits
- ✓ Build an infrastructure risk score engine
- ✓ Track and interpret DORA metrics for team performance

### Core Topics
- Predictive vs reactive operations: catching failures before they happen
- Time-series forecasting: moving averages, linear regression, ARIMA basics
- Capacity planning: "At current growth rate, disk fills in 14 days"
- Infrastructure risk scoring: weighted composite of CPU, memory, disk, error rate
- DORA metrics: Deployment Frequency, Lead Time for Changes, Change Failure Rate, MTTR
- DORA benchmarks: Elite, High, Medium, Low performance tiers
- SLO breach prediction: "At current trajectory, we breach SLO in 3 hours"

### Time-Series Forecasting Lab
Load 30 days of disk usage data (CSV). Fit a linear regression model. Predict: "Disk will reach 100% on [date]." Plot actual vs predicted with matplotlib. Repeat for CPU and memory.

### Risk Scoring Lab
Build a risk scoring engine in Python. Inputs: CPU (0–100), memory (0–100), disk (0–100), error rate (0–100). Weights: CPU=0.2, Memory=0.2, Disk=0.3, Errors=0.3. Output: composite risk score (0–100) with severity: Green (< 40), Yellow (40–70), Red (> 70).

### DORA Metrics Lab
Collect data from your GitHub Actions pipeline (Module 4). Calculate: How often did we deploy? What was the average time from commit to production? What % of deployments caused failures? How fast did we recover? Plot the DORA dashboard.

### Break / Fix Activity
Inject a disk fill pattern (1GB/hour growth). Run the forecasting model. Verify it predicts "disk full in 8 hours." Set an alert at the predicted time minus 2 hours. Confirm the alert fires before the actual failure.

